📋 Overview
This repository contains the code and materials for the paper:

Heterogeneous Penalties at the Top: Glass Ceilings, Hours Convexity, and Motherhood Selection Among Highly Educated Women in the U.S.

The project replicates the main findings of Bach et al. (2018) and extends them by studying three structural mechanisms behind wage penalties among highly educated White non-Hispanic women in the United States.

🔍 Main Findings
<table>
<tr>
<td width="33%" align="center">
🏛️ Glass Ceiling
Evidence of a glass ceiling at the top of the earnings distribution, with disproportionate wage penalties concentrated among high earners.
</td>
<td width="33%" align="center">
⏱️ Hours Convexity
Convex market returns to long hours, with an added penalty for women working 70+ hours per week.
</td>
<td width="33%" align="center">
👶 Motherhood Selection
A motherhood premium among full-time workers that appears to reflect selection, not causality.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

🗂️ Repository Structure
📦 heterogeneous-penalties-at-the-top
├── 📁 data/          — Datasets and data preparation files
├── 📁 codes/         — Replication and extension code
├── 📁 figures/       — Figures used in the paper and presentation
├── 📁 tables/        — Regression tables and outputs
├── 📁 presentation/  — Slides and presentation materials
└── 📁 report/        — Main paper and appendix

🛠️ Methods
This project employs a suite of modern causal inference and machine learning techniques:
MethodApplicationDouble Post-LassoHigh-dimensional variable selectionCausal ForestHeterogeneous treatment effect estimationDouble Machine Learning (DML)Semiparametric wage gap estimationDML-IRMInteractive regression modelPropensity Score WeightingSelection correctionCross-FittingSample-splitting for valid inference

📊 Data
2016 American Community Survey (ACS)
Restricted to:

✅ Full-time, year-round employed individuals
✅ Ages 25 to 65
✅ White non-Hispanic women with high educational attainment


📚 Reference

Bach, P., Chernozhukov, V., Kurz, M. S., & Spindler, M. (2018). Closing the U.S. Gender Wage Gap Requires Understanding Its Heterogeneity. arXiv preprint.


